# {{project_name}} — Agentic Task Board (worktree + PR edition)

A file-based work queue for autonomous agents. Every phase is a set of **features**
(folders), every feature a set of tasks. One agent takes one unit of work — one or more
tasks of a single feature — implements it in an **isolated git worktree**, and stops; the
complete feature ships as **ONE PR**. Nothing merges until *you* (the captain)
approve — unless you opt into **captain-gated auto-merge** for low-risk changes (off by
default; see below). Independent tasks run **in parallel** — each claim gets its own branch +
worktree.

Roles: **captain** = the human (approves/rejects), **firstmate** = the main Claude Code
session (spawns crew, monitors, relays), **crew** = the dev subagents in `.claude/agents/`,
**researcher** = drafts research briefs and backlog tasks, **reviewer** = read-only quality gate.

---

## Core ideas

1. **A task is ONE file that never moves.** `tasks/phase-N/<feature-slug>/T-XXX.md` —
   a phase contains feature folders, a feature folder contains tasks — with `status:` in its
   frontmatter as the single source of truth:
   `backlog → in-progress → in-review → changes-requested → done` (blocked is computed from deps).
2. **Claiming is atomic via git.** `claim.sh` creates branch `task/<id>` — git ref creation is
   atomic, so two agents claiming simultaneously get exactly one winner. No status database,
   no file moves, no double-booking.
3. **Worktrees give parallelism.** Each claim materializes `.worktrees/<id>` on its own branch.
   Agents on independent tasks never touch each other's files.
4. **The PR is the approval gate.** Agents commit *only on their task branch* and open a PR.
   Merge happens only after your approval. On reject, the task goes to `changes-requested` —
   **not** back to backlog — and the same owner resumes in the same worktree.
5. **Contracts unlock parallelism.** When task B only needs task A's *interface*, don't chain
   B on A. Create a small `kind: contract` task that writes the agreed interface (API shape,
   schema, file format) to `docs/contracts/<name>.md`; both A and B depend on the contract,
   run in parallel, and a later task may revise the contract if reality disagrees.
6. **Features ship as ONE PR — and grouping is a real folder, not a tag.** Inside a phase,
   put every task belonging to the same user-facing feature in the SAME FOLDER:
   `tasks/phase-N/<feature-slug>/T-XXX.md`. The folder name IS the feature slug — there is
   no field to keep in sync; a task's location is its feature. The feature is worked in ONE
   shared worktree (`.worktrees/feat-<slug>`, branch `feat/<slug>`) — up to 3 crew agents
   may share it (each on its own tasks/files, coordinated by the firstmate) — and it is
   submitted ONCE when the whole feature is implemented: one complete, reviewable PR per
   feature instead of a fragmented PR per task. Within-feature `depends_on` orders the
   tasks; it doesn't block claiming the next one in the same worktree (the firstmate
   sequences dependent tasks). Approve/reject/unclaim on any task of a feature applies to
   the whole feature. EVERY task lives in a feature folder — one-off chores, contracts,
   and epics get their own small (even single-task) feature folder rather than sitting
   directly in `tasks/phase-N/`.
7. **Phases are capped at 5 features.** A phase is a build-order bucket of feature
   folders and nothing else. Create the next `tasks/phase-(N+1)/` only once the current
   phase already holds 5 feature folders.

## Folder layout

```
tasks/phase-N/               # a phase = up to 5 feature folders, nothing else
├── <feature-slug>/          # e.g. tasks-ui-v3 — the folder name IS the feature
│   ├── T-011.md
│   └── T-012.md
└── <another-feature>/       # even a one-off chore/contract/epic gets its own folder
    └── T-013.md
```

> Legacy note: task files created directly in `tasks/phase-N/` before this rule keep
> working (own `task/<id>` branch + PR), but NEW tasks are never created outside a
> feature folder.

## Classification

| Field | Values | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `phase` (+ folder) | 0–N | build order (a phase holds at most 5 features) |
| `area` | {{areas_table}} | routes tasks to the right crew member (`./next.sh --area <area>`) |
| `kind` | `feature` `chore` `milestone` `epic` `contract` | epics are decomposed, never implemented directly; contracts pin interfaces |
| `complexity` | `trivial` `standard` `complex` | effort estimate set at task creation; drives `model` |
| `model` | `haiku` `sonnet` `opus` | Claude model the crew agent runs on (see Model routing) |
| `depends_on` | task ids | a task is claimable only when all deps are `done` |

Feature membership is NOT a frontmatter field — it's the task file's folder (see Folder
layout above and core idea 6).

## Model routing

Whoever creates a task (researcher, firstmate decomposing an epic, or the captain) analyses
its complexity and sets `complexity:` + `model:` in the frontmatter. The firstmate — which
itself runs on a high model — reads `model:` when spawning the crew subagent for a task and
passes it as the Agent-tool model override. High model orchestrates; work is delegated to
the cheapest model that can do it well.

| `complexity` | `model` | Use for |
|---|---|---|
| `trivial` | `haiku` | mechanical changes, no design decisions: renames, config tweaks, doc updates, copy changes, adding a field to an existing pattern |
| `standard` | `sonnet` | typical single-area feature/chore with clear acceptance criteria — **the default when unsure** |
| `complex` | `opus` | architectural or cross-cutting changes, ambiguous requirements, hard debugging, epic decomposition, contract design, security-sensitive work |

Rules of thumb: vague acceptance criteria or >5 files touched bumps a task up one tier;
a missing `model:` field means `sonnet`. The captain can always override by editing the
frontmatter before the task is claimed.

