## Lifecycle

```
                 claim.sh (atomic branch+worktree)      submit.sh (push + PR)
   backlog ────────────────────────► in-progress ────────────────────► in-review
      ▲                                    ▲                              │
      │ unclaim.sh (abandon)               │ resume in same worktree      │ human approves & merges PR,
      │                                    │                              │ then approve.sh (sync+cleanup)
      └───────────────                changes-requested ◄── reject.sh ────┤
                                                                          ▼
                                                                        done
```

## Agent protocol (follow exactly)

1. `./next.sh [--area <area>]` — see what's claimable (or resumable).
2. `./claim.sh <task-id> <your-agent-id>` — atomic claim; creates/reuses the feature's
   shared `.worktrees/feat-<slug>` on branch `feat/<slug>` (a legacy task sitting directly
   in `tasks/phase-N/` still gets its own `.worktrees/<id>` on `task/<id>`). On
   `CANNOT CLAIM`/`BLOCKED`, pick another. **Never work unclaimed.**
   The feature's tasks all live in its shared worktree (up to 3 crew
   may work there — stay on your own task's files). Claim each task with `claim.sh` before
   starting it, implement in the shared worktree, and only submit (step 4) after the
   feature's LAST task is implemented — whoever finishes last submits.
3. `cd` into the worktree and implement **only inside the worktree**. Add code comments.
   Commit on the work branch as you go (never on `main`, never push `main`).
4. `./submit.sh <task-id>` — merges `main` into the work branch if it moved since claim,
   commits leftovers, pushes, opens the PR (with `gh`), and flips status to `in-review`.
   If the merge conflicts, it stops and prints the conflicted files instead of pushing —
   resolve them in the worktree (judgment call: check whether the file was independently
   duplicated by another task first; if so the two copies are usually functionally
   identical), `git add`/`git commit`, then re-run `./submit.sh <task-id>`. Then **stop
   and report**. For a feature, `submit.sh` refuses while any of the feature's tasks is
   still in backlog, and otherwise flips ALL of them to in-review and opens ONE PR for
   the complete feature.
5. If the human requests changes (status `changes-requested`): resume in the *same* worktree,
   fix, and `./submit.sh` again — it updates the same PR.

Token tip: if `graphify-out/` exists at the repo root, query the knowledge graph (graphify
skill) to orient yourself before reading many files — it is far cheaper than broad exploration.

## Human (captain) protocol

- Review the PR on GitHub (or `git diff main...task/<id>` / `main...feat/<slug>` locally).
- **Approve path:** approve & merge the PR on GitHub, then `./approve.sh <id>` — verifies the
  merge, fast-forwards main, flips status to `done`, removes worktree + branch, commits the
  board state. (No remote / offline: `./approve.sh <id> --local` reviews-then-merges locally.)
  For a feature PR, pass any one of its task ids — every in-review task of the feature
  finalizes together.
- **Reject path:** `./reject.sh <id> "what to fix"` — status → `changes-requested`, reason
  appended to the task file; owner and worktree are kept (NOT sent to backlog). On a feature,
  all in-review siblings move back together and the owner resumes in the shared worktree.
- Stuck/abandoned claim: `./unclaim.sh <id> [--force]`.

## Auto-merge (optional, captain-gated, OFF by default)

To stop hand-approving trivially safe PRs, the captain can let the firstmate merge them
automatically. It stays fully manual until you opt in.

- **Enable / disable (your kill switch):** set `auto_merge.enabled` to `true`/`false` in
  `.helm-kit.json`. While off, nothing changes.
- **How it decides:** the reviewer gate emits a `RISK: low|medium|high` rating. When enabled,
  the firstmate runs `./auto-approve.sh <id> low` only for an `APPROVE`/`APPROVE WITH NITS`
  verdict rated `low`; everything else still routes to you.
- **The hard guard (can't be talked around):** `auto-approve.sh` re-scans the diff itself and
  **refuses** — routing to you — if it touches either deny-list, regardless of the rating:
  - **control plane** — `tasks/**`, `.claude/**`, `CLAUDE.md`, `AGENTS.md`, `.helm-kit.json`
    (the workflow's own scripts, agent/firstmate instructions, hooks, and manifest). So Claude
    can never rewrite the rules — or the approve scripts, or the reviewer — via an auto-merge.
  - **high-blast-radius** — the project globs in `auto_merge.deny_globs` (e.g. migrations, the
    DB layer, audio capture, the LLM/provider layer, `.env`, dependency/build files).
- **Audit trail:** every auto-merge appends a line to `tasks/auto-merge.log` (committed with
  the board) so you can review what merged without you.

## Running crew in parallel

Crew definitions live in `.claude/agents/`:

{{personas_bullets}}
- **researcher** — researches topics, writes briefs to `docs/research/`, drafts backlog tasks.
- **reviewer** — read-only safety/quality gate; runs automatically on every `submit.sh`.

Ways to run them:

1. **Orchestrated (recommended):** in the main {{project_name}} Claude Code session
   (the firstmate), say e.g. *"Run the next two ready tasks in parallel."* The firstmate
   spawns the right crew subagents in the background, each claims its own task (atomically —
   no collision), works in its own worktree, opens its PR, and reports back. The firstmate
   monitors and relays; you just review the PRs.
2. **Manual:** open terminals, run `claude` in each, and tell each one which crew member to
   act as and which area to take.

Because claims are atomic and worktrees are isolated, any number of agents can run
concurrently; `depends_on` keeps truly dependent work sequential. Features add a second
axis: a feature's tasks are worked in its ONE shared worktree by up to 3 crew agents (each
on its own tasks/files — `claim.sh` refuses a 4th agent), the firstmate sequences
within-feature dependencies, and the feature ships as ONE PR when complete. The firstmate defaults to
at most **{{max_parallel_agents}}** crew subagents at once for this project (a cost/context
preference set at `helm init` time — see `max_parallel_agents` in `.helm-kit.json`, or
`helm init --max-parallel N`), queuing the rest and backfilling as agents finish. Ask the
firstmate to raise or lower it for a session if you want more or less parallelism.

## Scripts

| Script | Who | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `next.sh [--area X]` | agent | claimable + resumable tasks |
| `board.sh` | anyone | full board grouped by status |
| `claim.sh <id> <agent>` | agent | atomic claim → branch + worktree (feature tasks share `feat/<slug>`) |
| `submit.sh <id> [--local]` | agent | commit, push, open PR, → in-review (whole feature: one PR) |
| `approve.sh <id> [--local]` | human | after PR merge: sync main, cleanup, → done (whole feature) |
| `auto-approve.sh <id> <risk> [--local]` | firstmate | low-risk fast path: merge + finalize, only when `auto_merge.enabled` and the diff clears the deny-lists |
| `reject.sh <id> "reason"` | human | → changes-requested (owner keeps task; whole feature) |
| `unclaim.sh <id> [--force]` | either | abandon a claim → backlog (whole feature) |

> **GitHub note:** with a configured `origin` remote and the GitHub CLI (`brew install gh &&
> gh auth login`), `submit.sh` opens PRs automatically. Without them, use `--local` mode:
> `submit.sh <id> --local` and `approve.sh <id> --local`.

